click the three dots to forget it

00:21:30.455 --> 00:21:32.691
and go through the pairing process again.

00:21:32.691 --> 00:21:34.493
Once you're satisfied everything is connected,

00:21:34.493 --> 00:21:36.461
it's time to check your network config.

00:21:36.461 --> 00:21:37.963
Windows has a firewall built in

00:21:38.730 --> 00:21:40.399
to protect your PC from unauthorized access

00:21:40.399 --> 00:21:41.300
from your network,

00:21:41.300 --> 00:21:44.069
but it has two modes that define how strict it will be.

00:21:44.069 --> 00:21:46.705
The first, nowadays the default, is public,

00:21:46.705 --> 00:21:49.341
which treats all incoming connections with suspicion

00:21:49.341 --> 00:21:52.411
unless you specifically allow an app to accept them.

00:21:52.411 --> 00:21:55.080
This is great for connecting to unsecured public Wi-Fi

00:21:55.080 --> 00:21:56.415
at your favorite coffee shop,

00:21:56.415 --> 00:21:57.482
but if you have a home network

00:21:57.482 --> 00:21:58.750
and you'd like to share files,

00:21:58.750 --> 00:22:00.752
you'll wanna change over your connection to private,

00:22:00.752 --> 00:22:02.788
which relaxes security to allow connection

00:22:02.788 --> 00:22:03.955
from your local network.

00:22:03.955 --> 00:22:05.991
You can change this by right clicking the network icon

00:22:05.991 --> 00:22:06.892
in the system tray,

00:22:06.892 --> 00:22:08.894
then clicking network and internet settings.

00:22:08.894 --> 00:22:10.495
Click on the network connection you wanna change,

00:22:10.495 --> 00:22:13.365
then toggle either private or public as desired.

00:22:13.365 --> 00:22:14.533
The next thing you'll wanna do,

00:22:14.533 --> 00:22:16.835
especially if you're sharing files on the network,

00:22:16.835 --> 00:22:18.370
is to set up your power options

00:22:18.370 --> 00:22:20.806
in the settings app under system, then power.

00:22:20.806 --> 00:22:22.974
Here you can set when your PC goes to sleep,

00:22:22.974 --> 00:22:24.376
when your screens go to sleep,

00:22:24.376 --> 00:22:26.678
and how aggressively your PC should try to optimize

00:22:26.678 --> 00:22:28.647
for performance or power usage.

00:22:28.647 --> 00:22:30.716
By default, Windows will set your PC to sleep

00:22:30.716 --> 00:22:31.950
after 10 minutes,

00:22:31.950 --> 00:22:34.152
but if you're a fan of accessing your PC remotely

00:22:34.152 --> 00:22:36.688
through an app like TeamViewer, Parsec, or Tailscale,

00:22:37.422 --> 00:22:38.590
or sharing files like we mentioned earlier,

00:22:38.590 --> 00:22:40.359
it'll be inaccessible while it's asleep

00:22:40.359 --> 00:22:42.461
without some very specific steps.

00:22:42.461 --> 00:22:45.330
In that case, you might wanna set your PC to never sleep,

00:22:45.330 --> 00:22:46.732
though that does mean you'll be missing out

00:22:46.732 --> 00:22:48.400
on those sleep power savings.

00:22:48.400 --> 00:22:50.335
You can, however, tune that power drop

00:22:50.335 --> 00:22:52.637
by searching for edit power plan in the start menu

00:22:52.637 --> 00:22:54.906
and clicking the change advanced power settings link

00:22:54.906 --> 00:22:56.908
in the vintage window that pops up.

00:22:56.908 --> 00:22:57.976
There are a bunch of settings here,

00:22:57.976 --> 00:23:00.178
ranging from when to turn off spinning hard disks,

00:23:00.178 --> 00:23:02.481
and how many power saving features are enabled

00:23:02.481 --> 00:23:05.650
for your Wi-Fi, USB, and PCI Express devices,

00:23:05.650 --> 00:23:07.619
as well as the ability to set the minimum

00:23:07.619 --> 00:23:09.721
and maximum performance of your CPU.

00:23:09.721 --> 00:23:12.124
These options can also be useful for troubleshooting things

00:23:12.124 --> 00:23:14.259
like periodic dropouts and disconnections.

00:23:14.259 --> 00:23:16.528
For example, if your USB cable is good

00:23:16.528 --> 00:23:17.763
and the port is good,

00:23:17.763 --> 00:23:20.232
try turning off USB selective suspend,

00:23:20.232 --> 00:23:21.800
or if your Wi-Fi is unreliable,

00:23:21.800 --> 00:23:24.035
you can try setting it to maximum performance.

